# ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
# Meal-Prep Bot — environment configuration
# Copy this file to config/.env and fill in your values.
# ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

# ─── Discord core ────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
# Bot token from https://discord.com/developers/applications → your application →
# "Bot" → "Reset Token". Required.
#
# When you create the bot, enable BOTH Privileged Gateway Intents:
#   • MESSAGE CONTENT INTENT  (so the bot can read your free-text replies in a
#     server channel — DMs to the bot are always readable, but enabling this
#     lets the bot be chatty in a server text channel too)
#   • SERVER MEMBERS INTENT is NOT required.
#
# Invite the bot to your server with the OAuth2 scopes:
#   bot  +  applications.commands
# and "Bot Permissions":
#   View Channels, Send Messages, Read Message History, Attach Files,
#   Embed Links, Manage Messages (only to clear its own component buttons).
DISCORD_BOT_TOKEN=

# Owner lock — the Discord user id of the sole account allowed to command the
# bot. STRONGLY recommended: without it, the first person to message the bot
# AFTER A RESTART hijacks it (the lock is auto-claimed on first message and
# persisted to the memory channel if this is unset, but setting it here is
# permanent and is the safe default).
#
# How to get your id: enable Developer Mode in Discord (Settings → Advanced),
# then click your own name → "Copy ID".
OWNER_DISCORD_ID=

# ─── Memory channel ──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
# A PRIVATE text channel in a Discord server (this is the "database").
# Create one and let only the bot + yourself see it.
# Set MEMORY_CHANNEL to the channel's numeric id (right-click → Copy ID) OR
# leave it blank and set MEMORY_CHANNEL_NAME to auto-detect by name.
# MEMORY_GUILD (server id) optionally narrows the name search (recommended when
# the bot is in several servers).
MEMORY_GUILD=
MEMORY_CHANNEL=
MEMORY_CHANNEL_NAME=MealPrepMemory

# How many newest channel messages to scan when looking up a memory doc. Docs
# are deleted when overwritten, so the channel only holds the latest version
# of each doc plus append-only log messages (feedback / plan_history). Default
# 400 is enough for a long-running single-user bot; raise it if you keep very
# old log entries around.
# MEMORY_DOC_SCAN=400

# ─── Scheduling ──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
# Your IANA timezone, e.g. Asia/Kolkata, America/New_York, Europe/London.
TIMEZONE=Asia/Kolkata

# Optional cron times (HH:MM, 24h, in your TIMEZONE). Defaults shown.
# The weekly plan fires on Sunday at CRON_WEEKLY_PLAN and plans the UPCOMING week.
# The prep-day job runs daily but only acts on your configured prep day.
# CRON_WEEKLY_PLAN=09:00
# CRON_DAILY_MENU=08:00
# CRON_PREP_DAY=08:05
# CRON_FEEDBACK=20:00
# CRON_LEARN=23:00

# ─── LLM (OpenAI-compatible endpoint) ────────────────────────────────────────
# Default target: OpenCode API → MiniMax M3 Free.
#   ⚠ The free promotion for MiniMax M3 Free appears to have ended; if you get a
#     401 ("Free promotion has ended"), either subscribe to OpenCode Go or point
#     LLM_MODEL at another available model. The architecture does not change.
#
# LLM_BASE_URL examples:
#   OpenCode : (your OpenCode provider base URL, OpenAI-compatible, ending in /v1)
#   Ollama   : http://localhost:11434/v1
#   OpenAI   : https://api.openai.com/v1
LLM_BASE_URL=
LLM_API_KEY=
LLM_MODEL=minimax-m3-free
LLM_TIMEOUT=120